REMARKS: DCA-1: Incident occurred at 1835 (1335L), first notification was made by Pentagon Police (Thomas Shannon) at 1925 (1425L). The Pentagon Police and Arlington PD received a report of a UAS being operated at 675 North Randolph Street, Arlington, VA. (approximately DCA300003.5). According to reports, the UAS was not being operated above the height of the building (unknown height / floors). It was also initially reported that they had received approval for the operation from the FAA. TSA NCRCC, FAA NCRCC and DCA ATCT were unable to locate any information on the operation. When Arlington PD arrived at the scene (1835Z /1335L),the UAS was flying and they ordered it down and the pilot complied immediately. They estimate that it had been flying for approximately 5 minutes. When FAANCRCC queried them reference having FAA approval, they replied that was not the case as the operator landed the aircraft immediately. POC for the Arlington PD: Lt Dan Murphy, 571-388-7853. UAS Operator: Edgar Romero, Washington Digital Media, 240-701-0797 who stated that he was working for the construction company who was erecting a pedestrian walkway for the owners of the building. MOR completed by DCA. MX notified.

REMARKS: The pilot of ASH6022 originally reported a bird strike at approximately the DCA315020, which is north of Sterling, VA just west of the Trump National Golf course.   The aircraft was heading south at altitude 2,700 feet setting up for a landing on runway 19L.  No injuries or damage to aircraft were reported.  The strike occurred about 0025 Zulu and aircraft landed 0029 Zulu without incident.  The pilot reported a bird strike, but upon inspection of the aircraft on the ground, the crew could not locate any normal signs of a bird strike, such as blood, feathers or anything biological.  The crew upon reflection said the strike did not sound like a bird which is usually a soft thud, but it sounded more like a sharp crack like a baseball bat.   Because of the lack of biological evidence and the sharp sound of impact, the crew believes they hit a UAS.  Fairfax County PD is being notified of this incident.  0154:  The Washington Operations Center (WOC) called the FAA DEN position and told them Mesa Airlines (ASH) had a maintenance crew re examine the aircraft and the airline is now changing this incident to Bird Strike.  The airline did not pass to the FAA why they changed this report.  NFA.
ACTYPE: CRJ7, CANADAIR, CL-600 Regional Jet CRJ-700
ORIGIN: KORF, ORF, NORFOLK INTL, NORFOLK, UNITED STATES
DEST: KIAD, IAD, WASHINGTON DULLES INTL, WASHINGTON, UNITED STATES

REMARKS: MIA TRACON called to report that security for Turkey Point Nuclear Power Plant had called them to report UAS activity over the facility. Turkey Point Power Plant is located 4NM SE of HST. HQ DEN took the name and number of the Security Company that works security for the plant. 0058 HQ DEN contacted Turkey Point Security. The Security Officer reported that they had 3 drones operating over the facility for roughly 50 minutes (1905-1950). The drones have since moved on, 2 went east over the water and one went west. Turkey Point Security disclosed they contacted HST and MIA to try to verify if the Facilities were aware of any approved drone operations with negative results. They also called the USCG to see if they could assist with the drones over the water. The drones were 3x3 ft with flashing red and white lights. HQ DEN checked with SOSC and confirmed there were no approved UAS operations in that area. HQ DEN then recommended Turkey Point Security contact Miami Dade 305-5985-6263 and report the drones and request their assistance in locating the operators of the UAS. Turkey Point Security also said they had a FBI number 305-944-9101 and HQ DEN recommended they make that report to them as well. 0120 Turkey Point Security made contact with Miami-Dade PD and they were going to send an officer out to take a report. HQ DEN left our direct number and requested Turkey Point Security contact us directly with any further updates.

Aircraft observed a UAS while orbiting at 3,800 feet, 3.5NM N of TUS. Evasive action was taken, PIC reported NMAC. AWO advised. 0640 TUS ATCT reports that AIR2 lost contact with the UAS in the vicinity of AVQ (Marana Regional Airport) after following it for over 60 minutes. UAS was observed climbing to an estimated 12,000 feet. AIR2 attempted to capture camera footage but was unable. UAS had been reported as a quad-copter but no further description due to nighttime conditions. AWO advised.

REMARKS: At 0155 ATCT observed a UAS fly over the field, W bound at 400-500 feet, 1 NM W of GSO Airport. Airport Operations notified at 336-665-5642. 0155 GSO ATCT reports to HQ DEN Airport Police are sweeping perimeter, UAS is still visible over departure corridor. ATCT is holding 2 IFR departures on RWY 23L due to proximity of UAS. 0210 UPDATE: GSO ATCT advised they utilized Opposite Direction Operations to depart RWY 5R with LBQ782 and VTM061. Arrivals will be utilizing RWY 23L. Local Police and Fire Department are continuing to sweep airport and perimeter for operator. 0238 UPDATE: GSO ATCT reports last sighting approximately 0230, UAS was north of the airport flying east/west lines. Operations returning to normal configuration, arriving and departing RWY 23L. GSO ATCT will file MOR. 0250 UPDATE: GSO ATCT observed the large UAS transition over the airport west to east, turning south at approximately 600 feet. UAS impacting airfield operations. Air Traffic Manager has directed ATCT to suspend operations UFN. Airfield Operations, Local Police and Fire Department continue to sweep airfield and perimeter for operator. 4 IFR arrivals potentially impacted for the 0400 hour, ZTL will track and report diversions and/or delays. 0335 UPDATE: NOTAM GSO 02/174 issued for UAS activity. AWO reports COVID-19 Vaccine Flight, FDX1041, is delaying departure at ORD due to UAS ongoing event. 0430 UPDATE: 0406 GSO ATCT reports UAS sighting by Airport Operations 1/2 NM N of Airport, N bound heading towards HWY 73. 0415 GSO ATCT reports UAS sighting by Airport Operations NE of the Airport on the extended centerline RWY 23L. Approximately 0400 ATCSCC has issued a Ground Stop for Air Traffic into GSO. ATCSCC reports 1 aircraft diversion, 7 aircraft in airborne holding, 7 aircraft captured in the Ground Stop as of 0430. FDX Operations still holding COVID-19 Vaccine flight on the ground in ORD to minimize risk of airborne holding or diversion. 0435 UPDATE: AMOC has been monitoring GSO UAS event and has observed no radar returns. GSO ATCT reports they have had no radar returns from UAS activity, however visual sightings reported by the ATCT, LEO and Airfield Operations. 0435 UPDATE: GSO Airfield Operations reports last verified/confirmed sighting was approximately 0300, UAS had steady green, flashing red lights and made no noise. Subsequent reports of UAS are unconfirmed by Airport Operations. 3 LEO Agencies are now involved in securing the airport perimeter and monitoring operations. 0440 CLOSEOUT: GSO ATCT reports to the ATCSCC they are now going to start accepting arrivals and departures, last sighting north of the airport. ATCSCC has notified FDX and stakeholders. AWO, JH, CT notified.
ORIGIN: KGSO, GSO, PIEDMONT TRIAD INTL, GREENSBORO, UNITED STATES

Another aircraft inbound from the southeast was issued a right downwind entry to avoid the reported position of the drone.  Another aircraft had reported drones to the west of the airport moments earlier but this was a different UAS due to location and timing. No further sightings are indicated. Local law enforcement was notified. MOR closed.

REMARKS: The Air Tactical Commander of the Chuweah Creek Fire called morning on 7/19/2021 to ZSE to report suspicious UAS activity. Reported the UAS was spotted following a tanker aircraft. The UAS was black on bottom and white on top and had an 8 foot wing (sloping) span. The UAS was able to fly 100+mph and made several abrupt maneuvers, to include following the maneuvers and turns of the tanker. The tanking operations were suspended as a result. 0145 HQ DEN acquired information from ZSE in regards to the UAS reported during firefighting operations. ZSE stated there was a TFR in place, 1/1362, for the firefighting operations. Colville Agency at 509-634-3100 was given as the POC.

ENY3961 advised C90 shortly after departing ORD RWY 9C that they had struck a UAS. ENY3961 was in a climbing left turn off ORD RWY 9C to a heading of 360 when they collided with the UAS. Chicago PD (CPD) was notified of the reported location to the airport.  CPD advised that the location is near a retention pond near the FAA Regional Office Complex.
